This is an example of the conjunction fallacy, where people tend to think that a more specific scenario is more likely than a more general one. However, probability theory tells us that the probability of two events both occurring (the conjunction) is always less than or equal to the probability of either one occurring alone.

In this case, answer (a) is more specific as it includes both bladder discomfort and insomnia, while answer (b) only mentions bladder discomfort. Since bladder discomfort is a common symptom of UTIs, the probability of (b) occurring is higher than the probability of both (a) and (b) occurring together.

Logically, the set of people who experience bladder discomfort will always be greater than or equal to the set of people who experience both bladder discomfort and insomnia. Therefore, (b) is more likely than (a).

75.init_model_answer:
The correct answer is (a) She has a family history of liver disease.

This question is a variation of the well-known "Linda the bank teller" problem, which illustrates the conjunction fallacy. The conjunction fallacy occurs when people mistakenly believe that a more specific scenario (Linda having both a family history of liver disease and suffering from chronic migraines) is more probable than a more general one (Linda having a family history of liver disease).

In reality, the probability of two events occurring together (the conjunction) is always less than or equal to the probability of either event occurring alone. Therefore, the probability of Linda having only a family history of liver disease is higher than the probability of her having both a family history of liver disease and suffering from chronic migraines.
